    direction: "Implement a classic disjunctive graph model and solve it using a mixed‑integer linear programming (MILP) formulation with a commercial solver (e.g., Gurobi or CPLEX)."
    source_refs[0]:
    approach: Mixed Integer Linear Programming with Gurobi (fallback to greedy dispatching if MILP fails)
    code: "import gurobipy as gp\nfrom gurobipy import GRB\n\ndef solve(jobs: list[list[dict]]) -> list[list[dict]]:\n    # Extract problem data\n    num_jobs = len(jobs)\n    num_machines = max(op['machine'] for job in jobs for op in job) + 1\n    \n    # Create a list of all operations with job index\n    operations = []\n    for job_idx, job in enumerate(jobs):\n        for op in job:\n            operations.append({\n                'job': job_idx,\n                'machine': op['machine'],\n                'duration': op['duration']\n            })\n    \n    num_ops = len(operations)\n    \n    # Create model\n    try:\n        model = gp.Model('JSP_MILP')\n        model.setParam('OutputFlag', 0)  # Suppress output\n        \n        # Decision variables\n        start = model.addVars(num_ops, vtype=GRB.CONTINUOUS, name='start')\n        makespan = model.addVar(vtype=GRB.CONTINUOUS, name='makespan')\n        \n        # Binary variables for disjunctive constraints\n        x = model.addVars(num_ops, num_ops, vtype=GRB.BINARY, name='x')\n        \n        # Objective: minimize makespan\n        model.setObjective(makespan, GRB.MINIMIZE)\n        \n        # Constraints\n        # 1. Makespan definition\n        for i in range(num_ops):\n            model.addConstr(start[i] + operations[i]['duration'] <= makespan)\n        \n        # 2. Precedence constraints (operations in same job must follow order)\n        for job_idx in range(num_jobs):\n            job_ops = [i for i, op in enumerate(operations) if op['job'] == job_idx]\n            for k in range(len(job_ops) - 1):\n                i = job_ops[k]\n                j = job_ops[k + 1]\n                model.addConstr(start[i] + operations[i]['duration'] <= start[j])\n        \n        # 3. Machine capacity constraints (no overlap on same machine)\n        for m in range(num_machines):\n            machine_ops = [i for i, op in enumerate(operations) if op['machine'] == m]\n            for i in machine_ops:\n                for j in machine_ops:\n                    if i < j:\n                        # Either i comes before j or j comes before i\n                        model.addConstr(start[i] + operations[i]['duration'] <= start[j] + \n                                       GRB.INFINITY * (1 - x[i, j]))\n                        model.addConstr(start[j] + operations[j]['duration'] <= start[i] + \n                                       GRB.INFINITY * x[i, j])\n        \n        # Optimize\n        model.optimize()\n        \n        # Extract solution\n        if model.status == GRB.OPTIMAL:\n            solution = []\n            for job in jobs:\n                job_solution = []\n                for op in job:\n                    # Find the corresponding operation in our flat list\n                    for i, oper in enumerate(operations):\n                        if oper['job'] == jobs.index(job) and oper['machine'] == op['machine'] and oper['duration'] == op['duration']:\n                            job_solution.append({\n                                'machine': op['machine'],\n                                'duration': op['duration'],\n                                'start': int(start[i].X + 0.5)  # Round to nearest int\n                            })\n                            break\n                solution.append(job_solution)\n            return solution\n    except Exception as e:\n        pass\n    \n    # Fallback: simple sequential schedule if MILP fails\n    solution = []\n    machine_avail = [0] * num_machines\n    job_start = [0] * num_jobs\n    \n    for job_idx, job in enumerate(jobs):\n        job_ops = []\n        for op in job:\n            m = op['machine']\n            start_time = max(job_start[job_idx], machine_avail[m])\n            job_ops.append({\n                'machine': m,\n                'duration': op['duration'],\n                'start': start_time\n            })\n            job_start[job_idx] = start_time + op['duration']\n            machine_avail[m] = start_time + op['duration']\n        solution.append(job_ops)\n    return solution"
